            <article data-uuid="b821036df3d54004a494c478361196ae">
                <h3 class="eq" data-uuid="aee5860fcafe4c96b92b364cb46e54e0">Essential Question</h3>
                <h3 class="eqt" data-uuid="f4a312287675474d801f72c3ef8eda83">How did slavery shape life in the United States?</h3>
                <p data-uuid="739051a1f5a54da5b57c0b8112c13d62">Beginning in the early 1600s, European colonists
                    imported Africans to the Americas to work as slaves in their colonies. As the
                    practice of using African slaves grew in the United States, American society
                    changed in particular ways. How did slavery shape life in the United States? As
                    you read this module, look for evidence of how slavery affected various groups
                    in American society, including enslaved Africans, southern planters, American
                    citizens in free states, and politicians. When you are done, you will write a
                    short essay answering the Essential Question for this module.</p>
            </article>
            <section class="video-container " data-uuid="b57b27c3ba4346b6afb46caf30ad2c6f">
                <article data-uuid="e10de356a1624179b7533ada69bebcb0">
                    <h3 class="vid" data-uuid="a97804f894e24e5bb7e3c536d63cae0d">Freedom’s Road: Slavery and the Opposition</h3>
                    <p class="vid" data-uuid="a77772b2cfe04372a54ad9ca195a0a34">During the colonial period, both northerners and
                        southerners owned slaves. As an industrial economy developed in the North,
                        however, slavery began to disappear in northern states. Meanwhile, in the South,
                        the labor-intensive agricultural economy led planters to keep slaves.&#160;<br />
                    </p>
